cff-version: 1.2.0
title: "Governance-as-Infrastructure: From Audit to Runtime"
message: "If you use this work, please cite it using the metadata from this file."
type: software
authors:
  - family-names: Shatny
    given-names: Michael
    orcid: "https://orcid.org/0009-0006-2011-3258"
doi: "10.5281/zenodo.21010922"  # concept DOI — always resolves to the latest version
repository-code: "https://github.com/semanticintent/governance-as-infrastructure"
abstract: >-
  Governance-as-Infrastructure (GaI) proposes that governance — traditionally
  a document, review, or audit applied after a system has produced something —
  can be compiled into runtime infrastructure: a Governed Constraint Set that
  operates before any artifact exists and gates execution on it. Where
  Methodology-as-Infrastructure compiles how to think and Intent-as-Infrastructure
  compiles what to reach into, GaI compiles what must be true, with the human
  reserved at the moment of formalization rather than the moment of consequence.
  Four properties are required: Pre-execution (before any artifact/agent),
  Constraint-formalized (an explicit, machine-checkable Governed Constraint Set),
  Residue-sovereign (the unresolvable residue is a first-class, provable artifact),
  and Human-as-primitive-at-formalization (execution gates on human-acknowledged
  residue). The CAL publishing pipeline serves as the primary case study, including
  the UC-236 incident that turned its implicit governance into an explicit, gating
  constraint set. GaI is the infrastructure counterpart of Governance-Driven Design
  and the upstream completion of the as-Infrastructure progression
  (IaC -> PaC -> MaI -> IaI -> GaI).
